naltrexone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Competitive opioid receptor antagonist","Dopamine reuptake inhibitor","N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor antagonist","Opioid receptor partial agonist","Gamma-aminobutyric acid receptor agonist"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENaltrexone acts as a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive opioid receptor antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E at mu, kappa, and delta opioid receptors. By blocking these receptors, naltrexone reduces alcohol cravings through interference with endogenous opioid reward pathways. This mechanism helps prevent relapse in both alcohol and opioid dependence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine reuptake inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of certain antidepressants and stimulants\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-methyl-D-aspartate receptor antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of ketamine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid receptor partial agonist\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes buprenorphine\u0027s mechanism in opioid dependence treatment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-aminobutyric acid receptor agonist\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of benzodiazepines and alcohol\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENaltrexone\u0027s effectiveness in alcohol dependence demonstrates the importance of opioid pathways in alcohol reward and craving.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Naltrexone is a competitive antagonist at mu, kappa, and delta opioid receptors.","Naltrexone reduces alcohol cravings by blocking endogenous opioid reward pathways.","Naltrexone is used in both alcohol and opioid dependence treatment."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50632"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14738"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50632"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:22:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:23:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7431"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65195"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synon